# System Architecture

This document describes the high-level architecture of a centralized
cryptocurrency trading platform and the responsibilities of its core
components.

The platform supports spot trading, OTC trading, and C2C (P2P) trading.


## High-Level Architecture
![image alt](https://github.com/rohit-261093/Cryptocurrency-exchange/blob/530cf59855bd8833556d5abc6c9e9b8970c1c62f/Crypto.png)


## Architecture Layers

### 1. Frontend Layer

The frontend layer provides user-facing interfaces for interacting with
the platform.

**Components**
- Android App
- iOS App
- PC Web
- Mobile Web

**Responsibilities**
- User authentication
- Order placement
- Account and balance display
- Real-time market data display

---

### 2. Access Layer

The access layer exposes platform functionality to clients.

**Components**
- Web
- API
- WebSocket

**Responsibilities**
- Handle synchronous API requests
- Deliver real-time updates (prices, order status)
- Enforce access control and rate limiting

---

### 3. Unified Gateway Routing

**Component**
- Nginx

**Responsibilities**
- Centralized routing for all inbound traffic
- Load balancing across backend services
- TLS termination and request forwarding

---

### 4. Business Layer

The business layer implements core trading and account logic.

#### Matchmaking Engine
- Maintains order books for trading pairs
- Matches buy and sell orders based on price-time priority
- Publishes trade execution events

#### OTC / C2C Service
- Supports off-order-book trading
- Enables peer-to-peer trades with escrow
- Manages negotiated and fixed-price trades

#### Marketing Service
- Manages promotions and referral programs
- Calculates trading incentives and rewards

#### User Center Service
- Manages user profiles and authentication data
- Handles KYC status and account metadata

#### Wallet Service
- Manages user balances
- Locks funds during order placement
- Applies balance updates after trade execution
- Interfaces with blockchain nodes for deposits and withdrawals

---

### 5. Data Layer

The data layer stores transactional and operational data.

#### MongoDB
- Stores semi-structured or historical data
- Used for flexible data models

#### MySQL
- Primary relational datastore
- Stores orders, trades, balances, and ledgers
- Acts as the system of record

#### Redis
- In-memory data store
- Used for order books, caches, and real-time state

#### Kafka
- Event streaming platform
- Delivers trade, wallet, and system events asynchronously

---

### 6. Blockchain Node Layer

The blockchain layer enables interaction with external networks.

**Components**
- BTC Node
- ETH Node
- XRP Node
- Other supported blockchain nodes

**Responsibilities**
- Monitor deposits
- Broadcast withdrawals
- Track transaction confirmations
